WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.000
Sherlock Holmes and The Red Circle

00:13.000 --> 00:16.000
by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle

00:18.000 --> 00:21.000
copyright, black cat publishing

00:31.000 --> 00:35.000
Sir Arthur Conan Doyle

00:35.000 --> 00:42.000
Sir Arthur Conan Doyle was born in Edinburgh, Scotland, on 22 May 1859.

00:42.000 --> 00:46.000
When he was a young boy, he liked reading books.

00:46.000 --> 00:52.000
In 1876, he began studying medicine at Edinburgh University.

00:52.000 --> 00:56.000
One of his professors was Dr Joseph Bell.

00:57.000 --> 01:02.000
Dr Bell watched his patients closely so that he could understand their illness.

01:02.000 --> 01:08.000
Later, Dr Bell became Conan Doyle's model for Sherlock Holmes.

01:08.000 --> 01:12.000
In 1882, Conan Doyle became a doctor.

01:12.000 --> 01:17.000
He did not have many patients, so he began writing his first Sherlock Holmes story,

01:17.000 --> 01:21.000
a study in scarlet, 1887.

01:21.000 --> 01:24.000
The story was a big success.

01:25.000 --> 01:31.000
In 1891, he wrote Sherlock Holmes stories for a monthly magazine called The Strand.

01:31.000 --> 01:38.000
Soon, the clever detective and his friend Dr Watson became very popular in Great Britain.

01:38.000 --> 01:44.000
When Conan Doyle stopped writing Sherlock Holmes stories, his readers got angry.

01:44.000 --> 01:49.000
Finally, in 1901, he started writing another Sherlock Holmes adventure,

01:49.000 --> 01:52.000
called The Hound of the Baskervilles.

01:52.000 --> 01:54.000
A lot of other stories followed.

01:54.000 --> 01:56.000
His readers were very pleased,

01:56.000 --> 02:01.000
and he continued writing about the famous detective until 1927.

02:01.000 --> 02:06.000
Some famous Sherlock Holmes books are The Sign of Four, 1890,

02:06.000 --> 02:10.000
The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes, 1892,

02:10.000 --> 02:13.000
The Return of Sherlock Holmes, 1905,

02:13.000 --> 02:16.000
The Valley of Fear, 1915,

02:16.000 --> 02:21.000
and The Case Book of Sherlock Holmes, 1927.

02:21.000 --> 02:27.000
The Red Circle is part of the book, His Last Bow, 1917.

02:27.000 --> 02:32.000
Conan Doyle died in England on the 7th of July, 1930.

02:36.000 --> 02:39.000
Sherlock Holmes and Dr Watson.

02:39.000 --> 02:45.000
The story you are going to read takes place in London at the start of the 20th century.

02:45.000 --> 02:49.000
It is about London's famous fictional detective, Sherlock Holmes,

02:49.000 --> 02:53.000
and his good friend, Dr Watson.

02:53.000 --> 02:58.000
Dr Watson helps Holmes with his detective cases.

02:58.000 --> 03:02.000
When Sherlock Holmes moved to London in 1874,

03:02.000 --> 03:06.000
he did not have much money, and his family had to help him.

03:06.000 --> 03:13.000
In 1881, he decided to share the cost of his rooms at 221 B Baker Street

03:13.000 --> 03:16.000
with Dr John H. Watson,

03:16.000 --> 03:21.000
and this is how Holmes and Watson became good friends.

03:21.000 --> 03:24.000
Watson tells us a lot of things about Holmes.

03:24.000 --> 03:30.000
He is not a difficult person to live with because he is quiet and has regular habits.

03:30.000 --> 03:37.000
For example, he usually goes to bed around ten at night and gets up very early in the morning.

03:37.000 --> 03:40.000
He works on his cases with a lot of energy,

03:40.000 --> 03:46.000
but sometimes he gets very bored and sits in the living room and does nothing.

03:46.000 --> 03:53.000
Watson also tells us that he is untidy and his desk is always full of papers.

03:53.000 --> 03:57.000
Mrs Hudson is the housekeeper who tidies the rooms.

03:57.000 --> 04:03.000
We know that Holmes plays the violin and wears Persian slippers at home.

04:03.000 --> 04:08.000
He often uses chemistry equipment to help him solve cases.

04:08.000 --> 04:19.000
Holmes is an excellent detective, and he often surprises Watson with his solutions to difficult cases.

04:19.000 --> 04:25.000
Chapter 1, Mrs Warren's problem.

04:25.000 --> 04:31.000
Well, Mrs Warren, I'm sorry, but I can't help you. I have other things to do.

04:31.000 --> 04:35.000
Said Sherlock Holmes, looking at the papers on his desk.

04:35.000 --> 04:38.000
But Mrs Warren did not go away.

04:38.000 --> 04:41.000
You helped my lodger, Mr Hobbs, last year?

04:41.000 --> 04:44.000
Said Mrs Warren, looking at Holmes.

04:44.000 --> 04:46.000
Yes, I remember.

04:46.000 --> 04:48.000
Said Holmes.

04:48.000 --> 04:51.000
Mr Hobbs said you are a kind, helpful man.

04:51.000 --> 04:53.000
Why can't you help me?

04:53.000 --> 04:55.000
Asked Mrs Warren.

04:55.000 --> 04:58.000
Holmes looked at her and said...

04:58.000 --> 05:02.000
All right, Mrs Warren, tell me about your problem.

05:02.000 --> 05:07.000
I understand your new lodger always stays in his rooms and you never see him.

05:07.000 --> 05:10.000
There's nothing strange about that.

05:10.000 --> 05:13.000
But I'm really afraid and I can't sleep.

05:13.000 --> 05:15.000
Said Mrs Warren.

05:15.000 --> 05:20.000
I hear his quick footsteps from morning to night, but I never see him.

05:20.000 --> 05:22.000
Why is he hiding?

05:22.000 --> 05:27.000
My husband is worried too, but he is away all day at work.

05:27.000 --> 05:32.000
I'm alone at home with the girl who helps me clean and I'm very frightened.

05:32.000 --> 05:35.000
Holmes looked at her kindly and said...

05:35.000 --> 05:38.000
Please sit down, Mrs Warren.

05:38.000 --> 05:44.000
Now, if I decide to help you, I must know everything. Do you understand?

05:44.000 --> 05:48.000
The smallest thing can be the most important.

05:48.000 --> 05:53.000
You said that the man came ten days ago and paid you for two weeks.

05:53.000 --> 05:54.000
Is that correct?

05:54.000 --> 05:55.000
Yes.

05:55.000 --> 05:56.000
Said Mrs Warren.

05:56.000 --> 06:02.000
I asked him to pay two pounds a week for a small sitting room and a bedroom at the top of the house.

06:02.000 --> 06:05.000
Well, asked Holmes.

06:05.000 --> 06:06.000
He said...

06:06.000 --> 06:11.000
I'll pay you five pounds a week if I can have the rooms on my conditions.

06:11.000 --> 06:13.000
I'm a poor woman, sir.

06:13.000 --> 06:18.000
Mr Warren doesn't make much money. I needed the extra money.

06:18.000 --> 06:21.000
The man gave me ten pounds and said...

06:21.000 --> 06:27.000
I can give you ten pounds every two weeks for a long time on my conditions.

06:27.000 --> 06:29.000
What were his conditions?

06:29.000 --> 06:30.000
Asked Holmes.

06:30.000 --> 06:37.000
Well, he wanted a key to the house and that was all right. Lodges off want a key.

06:37.000 --> 06:40.000
And he did not want anyone to disturb him.

06:40.000 --> 06:43.000
There is nothing strange about that, Mrs Warren.

06:43.000 --> 06:45.000
Said Holmes.

06:45.000 --> 06:50.000
No, but I never see him. No one sees him.

06:50.000 --> 06:54.000
He only went out of the house on the first night.

06:54.000 --> 06:57.000
Oh, he went out on the first night.

06:57.000 --> 06:58.000
Asked Holmes.

06:58.000 --> 06:59.000
Yes, sir.

06:59.000 --> 07:03.000
And he came back very late when we were all in bed.

07:03.000 --> 07:05.000
Said Mrs Warren.

07:05.000 --> 07:07.000
But his meals?

07:07.000 --> 07:08.000
Asked Holmes.

07:08.000 --> 07:13.000
Oh, we leave his meals on a chair outside his room when he rings the bell.

07:13.000 --> 07:14.000
Said Mrs Warren.

07:14.000 --> 07:17.000
And he rings again when he finishes eating.

07:17.000 --> 07:24.000
If he wants anything, he writes it in capital letters on a piece of paper and leaves it on the chair.

07:24.000 --> 07:26.000
He writes in capital letters.

07:26.000 --> 07:27.000
Asked Holmes.

07:27.000 --> 07:32.000
Yes, sir. Just the word in pencil and nothing more.

07:32.000 --> 07:33.000
Said Mrs Warren.

07:33.000 --> 07:39.000
Look, here are the notes he writes. This one says, soap.

07:39.000 --> 07:44.000
Here's another one that says, match. And this is one he wrote this morning.

07:44.000 --> 07:47.000
It says, daily gazette.

07:47.000 --> 07:51.000
I leave the newspaper with his breakfast every morning.

07:51.000 --> 07:57.000
Mrs Warren gave Holmes the two pieces of paper and he looked at them with interest.

07:57.000 --> 07:59.000
Oh, dear Watson.

07:59.000 --> 08:00.000
Said Holmes.

08:00.000 --> 08:03.000
This is really a bit strange.

08:03.000 --> 08:07.000
Why does this man write in capital letters?

08:07.000 --> 08:11.000
It is much easier and quicker to write normally.

08:11.000 --> 08:13.000
What do you think, Watson?

08:13.000 --> 08:18.000
He probably doesn't want Mrs Warren to see his handwriting, I said.

08:18.000 --> 08:19.000
But why?

08:19.000 --> 08:21.000
Asked Holmes.

08:21.000 --> 08:23.000
Perhaps you're right, Watson.

08:23.000 --> 08:28.000
But why are his messages so short? Why doesn't he write in sentences?

08:28.000 --> 08:32.000
I really don't know, I said.

08:35.000 --> 08:37.000
Chapter two.

08:37.000 --> 08:40.000
Secret messages.

08:40.000 --> 08:45.000
Holmes looked at the two pieces of paper carefully.

08:45.000 --> 08:47.000
This is interesting.

08:47.000 --> 08:48.000
He said.

08:48.000 --> 08:52.000
He writes the words with a violet colored pencil.

08:52.000 --> 08:59.000
Mrs Warren, you said that the man is not tall or short and has dark hair and a beard.

08:59.000 --> 09:00.000
How old is he?

09:00.000 --> 09:03.000
He's young, sir. Not over 30.

09:03.000 --> 09:05.000
Said Mrs Warren.

09:05.000 --> 09:07.000
Can you tell me something more about him?

09:07.000 --> 09:08.000
Asked Holmes.

09:08.000 --> 09:12.000
He spoke good English, but I'm sure he's a foreigner.

09:12.000 --> 09:14.000
Said Mrs Warren.

09:14.000 --> 09:15.000
Was he well dressed?

09:15.000 --> 09:16.000
Asked Holmes.

09:16.000 --> 09:20.000
Yes, he was very well dressed in dark clothes.

09:20.000 --> 09:22.000
Asked Mrs Warren.

09:22.000 --> 09:24.000
Did he tell you his name?

09:24.000 --> 09:25.000
Asked Holmes.

09:25.000 --> 09:26.000
No, sir.

09:26.000 --> 09:28.000
Asked Mrs Warren.

09:28.000 --> 09:31.000
Does he receive any letters or friends?

09:31.000 --> 09:32.000
Asked Holmes.

09:32.000 --> 09:33.000
No, sir.

09:33.000 --> 09:35.000
Asked Mrs Warren.

09:35.000 --> 09:39.000
Do you or the girl go into his room to clean it?

09:39.000 --> 09:41.000
Asked Holmes.

09:41.000 --> 09:43.000
No, sir. He does it.

09:43.000 --> 09:44.000
Said Mrs Warren.

09:44.000 --> 09:45.000
Goodness.

09:45.000 --> 09:46.000
Said Holmes.

09:46.000 --> 09:48.000
That is surprising.

09:48.000 --> 09:50.000
Did he have any luggage?

09:50.000 --> 09:54.000
He only had one big brown bag with him.

09:54.000 --> 09:56.000
Said Mrs Warren.

09:56.000 --> 09:59.000
We have to know more about him.

09:59.000 --> 10:00.000
Said Holmes.

10:00.000 --> 10:03.000
Did anything come out of that room?

10:04.000 --> 10:09.000
Mrs Warren took an envelope out of her bag and put it on the table.

10:09.000 --> 10:15.000
Inside the envelope there were two burnt matches and a cigarette stub.

10:15.000 --> 10:18.000
They were on his tray this morning.

10:18.000 --> 10:19.000
She said.

10:19.000 --> 10:23.000
I know that small things are important to you, Mr Holmes.

10:23.000 --> 10:26.000
Holmes picked them up and examined them.

10:26.000 --> 10:29.000
The matches aren't important, I think.

10:29.000 --> 10:32.000
He used them to light cigarettes.

10:32.000 --> 10:36.000
But this cigarette stub is very strange.

10:36.000 --> 10:38.000
You said the man has a beard.

10:38.000 --> 10:39.000
Yes, he does.

10:39.000 --> 10:41.000
Said Mrs Warren.

10:41.000 --> 10:43.000
I don't understand.

10:43.000 --> 10:45.000
Said Holmes.

10:45.000 --> 10:49.000
How can a man with a beard smoke a cigarette in that way?

10:49.000 --> 10:51.000
He will burn his beard.

10:51.000 --> 10:53.000
The cigarette stub is too short.

10:53.000 --> 10:57.000
Perhaps there are two people in the room, Mrs Warren.

10:57.000 --> 10:58.000
Oh no.

10:58.000 --> 11:01.000
He eats very little, not even enough for one person.

11:01.000 --> 11:03.000
Said Mrs Warren.

11:03.000 --> 11:08.000
At this point I think we must wait for a few more facts.

11:08.000 --> 11:09.000
Said Holmes.

11:09.000 --> 11:14.000
After all, he paid the rent and he does not cause trouble.

11:14.000 --> 11:18.000
If he wants to hide, it is not your business, Mrs Warren.

11:18.000 --> 11:22.000
We can't disturb him until there is a good reason.

11:22.000 --> 11:25.000
Now, I have a good picture of your problem.

11:25.000 --> 11:28.000
Please tell me if anything new happens.

11:29.000 --> 11:32.000
Thank you Mr Holmes and Dr Watson.

11:32.000 --> 11:36.000
Said Mrs Warren leaving the room.

11:36.000 --> 11:40.000
Well Watson, there are certainly some interesting things in this case.

11:40.000 --> 11:42.000
Said Holmes.

11:42.000 --> 11:48.000
I think the person in the rooms is probably not the one who rented them.

11:48.000 --> 11:49.000
Why?

11:49.000 --> 11:51.000
I asked surprised.

11:51.000 --> 11:54.000
Well, first of all, there is the cigarette stub.

11:54.000 --> 11:55.000
Said Holmes.

11:55.000 --> 12:00.000
And then the lodger went out only once after he rented the rooms.

12:00.000 --> 12:06.000
He came back, or someone came back, when everyone in the house was sleeping.

12:06.000 --> 12:11.000
Was the person who went out the same person who came back late at night?

12:11.000 --> 12:12.000
We don't know.

12:12.000 --> 12:16.000
The man who rented the rooms spoke English well.

12:16.000 --> 12:20.000
But the other person wrote, match and not matches.

12:21.000 --> 12:24.000
This person probably does not know English well.

12:24.000 --> 12:27.000
And that is why he writes short notes.

12:27.000 --> 12:33.000
Yes Watson, I think the person in the rooms is not the same person who rented them.

12:33.000 --> 12:37.000
How strange, I said.

12:37.000 --> 12:41.000
Well, there is one thing we can do to find out more.

12:41.000 --> 12:42.000
Said Holmes.

12:42.000 --> 12:48.000
The person in Mrs Warren's rooms is alone, and does not receive any letters or friends.

12:48.000 --> 12:52.000
How can he receive any news or messages from outside?

12:52.000 --> 12:55.000
Only by an advertisement in a newspaper.

12:55.000 --> 12:57.000
There is no other way.

12:57.000 --> 13:00.000
And we even know the newspaper.

13:00.000 --> 13:02.000
The Daily Gazette.

13:02.000 --> 13:09.000
Holmes opened a big book where he put the personal advertisement sections of the London newspapers.

13:09.000 --> 13:14.000
Here are the Daily Gazette personal advertisements of the last two weeks.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.000
Hmm.

13:16.000 --> 13:20.000
Lady with blue hat at Piccadilly Circus.

13:20.000 --> 13:23.000
Jimmy, don't break your mother's heart.

13:23.000 --> 13:25.000
These don't interest me.

13:25.000 --> 13:28.000
Ah, listen to this.

13:28.000 --> 13:32.000
I will find a way to send you messages.

13:32.000 --> 13:35.000
For now, this column, G.

13:35.000 --> 13:38.000
Look at the date of the newspaper.

13:38.000 --> 13:42.000
It's two days after Mrs Warren's lodger rented the rooms.

13:42.000 --> 13:48.000
This mysterious person understands English, even if he cannot write it.

13:48.000 --> 13:50.000
Perhaps we can find more.

13:50.000 --> 13:51.000
Said Holmes.

13:51.000 --> 13:52.000
Yes.

13:52.000 --> 13:53.000
Look.

13:53.000 --> 13:55.000
Three days later.

13:55.000 --> 13:56.000
Take care.

13:56.000 --> 13:58.000
The clouds will pass.

13:58.000 --> 13:59.000
G.

13:59.000 --> 14:03.000
There is nothing for another week, and then another message.

14:03.000 --> 14:07.000
If I send a message, remember the secret code.

14:07.000 --> 14:10.000
1A, 2B, and so on.

14:10.000 --> 14:13.000
You will hear from me soon, G.

14:13.000 --> 14:17.000
That was yesterday's paper, and there is nothing in today's.

14:17.000 --> 14:19.000
It could be the lodger.

14:19.000 --> 14:21.000
Let's wait a bit, Watson.

14:21.000 --> 14:24.000
We'll know more soon.

14:27.000 --> 14:30.000
Victorian writers.

14:30.000 --> 14:39.000
Sir Arthur Conan Doyle started writing his stories about Sherlock Holmes in the late 19th century, during Victorian times.

14:39.000 --> 14:45.000
A lot of Britain's greatest writers wrote at this time, and this inspired him.

14:45.000 --> 14:54.000
During the 19th century, educational possibilities were slowly getting better, and more and more people were learning to read and write.

14:54.000 --> 15:00.000
Without the radio, cinema, or television, reading was the favorite type of entertainment.

15:00.000 --> 15:06.000
People loved reading novels, newspapers, magazines, academic books, and even comics.

15:06.000 --> 15:14.000
In the 1850s, the government started building public libraries in towns and cities all over Great Britain.

15:14.000 --> 15:23.000
Books were too expensive to buy for most people, but in these new libraries, more people had the possibility to read a lot of different books.

15:23.000 --> 15:29.000
The Daily Telegraph, started in 1855, became the first penny paper.

15:29.000 --> 15:35.000
The paper was a big success, and quickly became the best-selling newspaper.

15:35.000 --> 15:40.000
Because of this, more and more people could read the newspaper every day.

15:40.000 --> 15:50.000
The first children's comics, with funny cartoons and adventures, also came out in the 1850s, and children had great fun reading them.

15:50.000 --> 15:57.000
In Victorian times, novels were sometimes published in chapters in magazines and newspapers.

15:57.000 --> 16:02.000
Every week or month, people could read a new chapter of a story.

16:02.000 --> 16:08.000
This continued for months, and sometimes years until the story was finished.

16:08.000 --> 16:13.000
As a result of all these changes, some authors became very popular.

16:13.000 --> 16:15.000
Here are some of them.

16:15.000 --> 16:20.000
Charles Dickens, 1812-1870

16:20.000 --> 16:24.000
As a child, Charles Dickens was poor.

16:24.000 --> 16:28.000
He left school at a young age to work in a factory for long hours.

16:28.000 --> 16:31.000
He never forgot this bad experience.

16:31.000 --> 16:38.000
His first novel was the Pickwick Papers, 1837, and it was a success.

16:38.000 --> 16:48.000
He wrote 14 important novels, including Oliver Twist, 1839, and David Copperfield, 1849-1850.

16:48.000 --> 16:53.000
He wrote about the poor people and the social problems at that time.

16:53.000 --> 16:57.000
Anna Sewell, 1820-1878

16:57.000 --> 17:02.000
In 1877, Anna Sewell wrote Black Beauty.

17:02.000 --> 17:06.000
It was about the life and adventures of a horse.

17:06.000 --> 17:14.000
After reading this book, people began to understand that animals were living creatures, and it was wrong to mistreat them.

17:14.000 --> 17:20.000
Wilkie Collins, 1824-1889

17:20.000 --> 17:28.000
In 1868, Wilkie Collins published The Moonstone with one of the first detectives in English fiction, Sergeant Cuff.

17:28.000 --> 17:34.000
The novel became very popular, and people started reading detective fiction.

17:34.000 --> 17:40.000
Lewis Carroll, 1832-1898

17:40.000 --> 17:48.000
Lewis Carroll wrote the first fantasy story for children called Alice's Adventures in Wonderland, 1865.

17:48.000 --> 17:51.000
It was a bestseller.

17:51.000 --> 17:59.000
Victorian children loved the book with its exciting adventures and beautiful illustrations by Sir John Tenniel.

17:59.000 --> 18:04.000
Robert Louis Stevenson, 1850-1894

18:05.000 --> 18:12.000
In 1883, Robert Louis Stevenson wrote a great adventure book for young people called Treasure Island.

18:12.000 --> 18:16.000
It was about a young boy's adventures with pirates at sea.

18:16.000 --> 18:24.000
He also wrote other adventure stories, like Kidnapped, 1886, and The Black Arrow, 1888.

18:24.000 --> 18:29.000
Rudyard Kipling, 1865-1936

18:29.000 --> 18:40.000
Rudyard Kipling wrote The Jungle Book, 1894, The Second Jungle Book, 1895, and Just So Stories, 1902.

18:40.000 --> 18:47.000
They were very popular with children. Most of the characters of these books were animals.

18:48.000 --> 18:55.000
Chapter 3, The Face in the Mirror

18:55.000 --> 19:01.000
The next morning, Holmes was sitting at his desk with a big smile on his face.

19:01.000 --> 19:03.000
Listen to this, Watson.

19:03.000 --> 19:06.000
He said, reading the newspaper aloud.

19:07.000 --> 19:17.000
Tall, red house with white windows, third floor, second window on left, after dark, G.

19:17.000 --> 19:23.000
This is a clear message. After breakfast, we'll go and visit Mrs. Warren's house.

19:23.000 --> 19:26.000
Good idea, I said.

19:26.000 --> 19:31.000
We got to Mrs. Warren's house and we waited for her in the sitting room.

19:31.000 --> 19:35.000
She suddenly ran into the room and said angrily,

19:35.000 --> 19:39.000
I must call the police, Mr. Holmes, but I wanted to talk to you first.

19:39.000 --> 19:42.000
That man must leave this house.

19:42.000 --> 19:45.000
Something terrible happened to my husband this morning.

19:45.000 --> 19:47.000
What happened to Mr. Warren?

19:47.000 --> 19:49.000
Asked Holmes.

19:49.000 --> 19:52.000
This morning he went to work before seven o'clock.

19:52.000 --> 19:57.000
He walked down the road a few steps and suddenly two men came up behind him.

19:57.000 --> 20:01.000
They threw a coat over his head and pushed him into a cab.

20:01.000 --> 20:06.000
They drove around for an hour and then opened the door and pushed him out on Hampstead Heath.

20:06.000 --> 20:12.000
When he got home, the poor man was very frightened and now he's sleeping upstairs.

20:12.000 --> 20:14.000
Very interesting.

20:14.000 --> 20:15.000
Said Holmes.

20:15.000 --> 20:18.000
Did he see the men? Did he hear them speak?

20:18.000 --> 20:20.000
No, he didn't.

20:20.000 --> 20:21.000
Said Mrs. Warren.

20:21.000 --> 20:24.000
But he thinks there were two or three men.

20:24.000 --> 20:27.000
And do you think this has something to do with your lodger?

20:27.000 --> 20:28.000
Asked Holmes.

20:28.000 --> 20:29.000
Of course.

20:29.000 --> 20:31.000
Said Mrs. Warren.

20:31.000 --> 20:33.000
My husband never had such a problem before.

20:33.000 --> 20:37.000
I don't want that lodger in this house. Money isn't everything.

20:37.000 --> 20:39.000
Wait a moment, please.

20:39.000 --> 20:40.000
Said Holmes.

20:40.000 --> 20:44.000
I think your lodger is in some kind of danger.

20:44.000 --> 20:48.000
Those men were probably waiting for him outside your door this morning.

20:48.000 --> 20:53.000
They thought your husband was the lodger because it was still dark at that time.

20:53.000 --> 20:58.000
When they discovered it was the wrong man, they let your husband go.

20:58.000 --> 21:00.000
What must I do?

21:00.000 --> 21:02.000
Asked Mrs. Warren.

21:02.000 --> 21:04.000
I want to see your lodger.

21:04.000 --> 21:05.000
Said Holmes.

21:05.000 --> 21:07.000
But how can you see him?

21:07.000 --> 21:09.000
Asked Mrs. Warren.

21:09.000 --> 21:11.000
No one can see him.

21:11.000 --> 21:15.000
He has to open the door and take the tray with his meal into his room.

21:15.000 --> 21:19.000
Watson and I can hide and watch him do it.

21:19.000 --> 21:22.000
Mrs. Warren thought for a moment and said...

21:22.000 --> 21:25.000
Yes, you can.

21:25.000 --> 21:29.000
There's a small cupboard near his room and I can put up a mirror.

21:29.000 --> 21:32.000
And if you are behind the door...

21:32.000 --> 21:34.000
Excellent idea.

21:34.000 --> 21:36.000
Said Holmes.

21:36.000 --> 21:38.000
When does he eat lunch?

21:38.000 --> 21:40.000
At about one o'clock.

21:40.000 --> 21:41.000
Good.

21:41.000 --> 21:42.000
Said Holmes.

21:42.000 --> 21:46.000
Dr. Watson and I will come to your house before one o'clock.

21:46.000 --> 21:49.000
Goodbye Mrs. Warren.

21:49.000 --> 21:53.000
At half past twelve we were outside Mrs. Warren's house.

21:53.000 --> 21:56.000
Holmes pointed to one of the house's opposite.

21:56.000 --> 21:58.000
Look Watson.

21:58.000 --> 21:59.000
He said.

21:59.000 --> 22:02.000
Tall red house with white windows.

22:02.000 --> 22:05.000
That's the house in the newspaper message.

22:05.000 --> 22:09.000
Now we know the place and the secret code.

22:09.000 --> 22:11.000
Our job is easy.

22:11.000 --> 22:12.000
Look.

22:12.000 --> 22:14.000
There's a two rent sign in the window.

22:14.000 --> 22:17.000
It must be an empty flat.

22:17.000 --> 22:18.000
Yes.

22:18.000 --> 22:19.000
I'm sure it is.

22:19.000 --> 22:22.000
I said looking at the red house.

22:22.000 --> 22:27.000
Holmes rang the bell of Mrs. Warren's house and she opened the door.

22:27.000 --> 22:30.000
I have everything ready for you.

22:30.000 --> 22:31.000
She said.

22:31.000 --> 22:34.000
Please come up and I'll show you the cupboard.

22:34.000 --> 22:36.000
Thank you Mrs. Warren.

22:36.000 --> 22:38.000
Said Holmes.

22:38.000 --> 22:42.000
Holmes and I followed Mrs. Warren upstairs quietly.

22:42.000 --> 22:46.000
The cupboard was a very good place to hide.

22:46.000 --> 22:51.000
Mrs. Warren put the mirror in a position so that we could see the door of the lodges' rooms.

22:51.000 --> 22:54.000
We sat down and waited.

22:54.000 --> 23:00.000
Then we heard the lodger ring for lunch and Mrs. Warren came up with the tray.

23:00.000 --> 23:05.000
She put it down on a chair near the closed door and left.

23:05.000 --> 23:12.000
We heard her heavy footsteps going down the stairs and we kept our eyes on the mirror.

23:12.000 --> 23:16.000
When is the lodger going to open the door?

23:16.000 --> 23:18.000
I whispered.

23:18.000 --> 23:21.000
Probably very soon.

23:21.000 --> 23:23.000
Holmes whispered back.

23:23.000 --> 23:28.000
Suddenly we heard the sound of a key opening the door.

23:28.000 --> 23:33.000
Two thin hands came out quickly and took the tray from the chair.

23:33.000 --> 23:37.000
But a moment later the hands put back the tray.

23:37.000 --> 23:43.000
I saw a beautiful but frightened face looking at the open door of the cupboard.

23:43.000 --> 23:48.000
Then the lodger's door closed quickly and the key turned.

23:48.000 --> 23:54.000
Everything was silent again and we went back downstairs.

23:54.000 --> 23:57.000
I will come back again this evening.

23:57.000 --> 23:59.000
Said Holmes to Mrs. Warren.

23:59.000 --> 24:04.000
I think we can discuss this better at Baker Street Watson.

24:04.000 --> 24:12.000
Chapter 4. Danger.

24:12.000 --> 24:14.000
I was right Watson.

24:14.000 --> 24:17.000
Said Holmes, sitting in his big arm chair.

24:17.000 --> 24:22.000
The lodger we just saw is not the man Mrs. Warren knows.

24:22.000 --> 24:25.000
It's a beautiful young woman.

24:25.000 --> 24:29.000
Yes, I said. And she saw us.

24:29.000 --> 24:32.000
Well, she saw something that frightened her.

24:32.000 --> 24:34.000
Said Holmes.

24:34.000 --> 24:37.000
Everything is a little clearer now, isn't it?

24:37.000 --> 24:42.000
A man and a woman come to London to get away from a dangerous situation.

24:42.000 --> 24:48.000
The man has some work that he must do and leaves the woman in a safe place.

24:48.000 --> 24:54.000
This was not easy, but he had a clever plan and he hid her well.

24:54.000 --> 24:58.000
Not even Mrs. Warren knows who the lodger is.

24:58.000 --> 25:02.000
She writes in capital letters because she has a woman's handwriting.

25:02.000 --> 25:06.000
She didn't want anyone to know about her.

25:06.000 --> 25:10.000
The man cannot come near the woman because their enemies could find her.

25:10.000 --> 25:13.000
So he writes messages in the newspapers.

25:13.000 --> 25:16.000
So far, everything is clear.

25:16.000 --> 25:18.000
But what is behind this?

25:18.000 --> 25:19.000
I asked.

25:19.000 --> 25:21.000
Ah, yes, Watson.

25:21.000 --> 25:22.000
Said Holmes.

25:22.000 --> 25:24.000
What is behind this?

25:24.000 --> 25:28.000
Mrs. Warren's problem is bigger than I thought.

25:28.000 --> 25:34.000
We saw the young woman's frightened face and we heard what happened to Mr. Warren.

25:34.000 --> 25:38.000
This is a matter of life and death, dear Watson.

25:38.000 --> 25:42.000
But the enemy does not know about the change of lodger.

25:42.000 --> 25:46.000
It is all very strange.

25:46.000 --> 25:51.000
It was a cold winter evening when we went back to Mrs. Warren's house.

25:51.000 --> 25:57.000
We decided to sit in her dark sitting room in front of the big window.

25:57.000 --> 26:02.000
From there we could see a light on the third floor of the red building.

26:02.000 --> 26:05.000
Someone is in that room.

26:05.000 --> 26:09.000
Said Holmes, moving closer to the window.

26:09.000 --> 26:11.000
I can see a dark figure.

26:11.000 --> 26:13.000
There he is again.

26:13.000 --> 26:18.000
He has a candle in his hand and he is looking out of the window.

26:18.000 --> 26:23.000
Now he is starting to send a message with the flame of the candle.

26:23.000 --> 26:27.000
Let's both try and read the message, Watson.

26:27.000 --> 26:28.000
One flash?

26:28.000 --> 26:30.000
That's an A.

26:30.000 --> 26:32.000
Now, how many flashes did he make?

26:32.000 --> 26:33.000
Twenty.

26:33.000 --> 26:34.000
Is that right, Watson?

26:34.000 --> 26:35.000
Yes.

26:35.000 --> 26:38.000
He made twenty flashes, I said.

26:38.000 --> 26:40.000
That means T.

26:40.000 --> 26:41.000
A.

26:41.000 --> 26:42.000
T.

26:42.000 --> 26:43.000
At.

26:43.000 --> 26:45.000
That's clear.

26:45.000 --> 26:47.000
But now another T.

26:47.000 --> 26:50.000
That's the beginning of a new word.

26:50.000 --> 26:53.000
Hmm?

26:53.000 --> 26:55.000
Ten tau.

26:55.000 --> 26:56.000
He stopped.

26:56.000 --> 26:58.000
That can't be the message.

26:58.000 --> 26:59.000
At.

26:59.000 --> 27:00.000
Ten tau.

27:00.000 --> 27:02.000
Doesn't mean anything.

27:02.000 --> 27:04.000
Perhaps it's three words.

27:04.000 --> 27:05.000
At.

27:05.000 --> 27:07.000
Ten tau.

27:07.000 --> 27:11.000
Or perhaps tau is part of the person's name.

27:11.000 --> 27:13.000
There it goes again.

27:13.000 --> 27:15.000
What's that?

27:15.000 --> 27:19.000
A-T-T-E.

27:19.000 --> 27:21.000
It's the same message again.

27:21.000 --> 27:24.000
How strange, Watson.

27:24.000 --> 27:27.000
Now he is sending a third message.

27:27.000 --> 27:28.000
At.

27:28.000 --> 27:30.000
Ten tau.

27:30.000 --> 27:32.000
He left the window.

27:32.000 --> 27:35.000
I think the message is finished.

27:35.000 --> 27:37.000
What do you think, Watson?

27:37.000 --> 27:41.000
I don't know, Holmes, I said.

27:41.000 --> 27:44.000
Suddenly, Holmes laughed and said.

27:44.000 --> 27:49.000
Why, of course, the message is in Italian.

27:49.000 --> 27:54.000
The A at the end of the word means that the message is for a woman.

27:54.000 --> 27:59.000
It means be careful, be careful, be careful.

27:59.000 --> 28:01.000
How's that, Watson?

28:01.000 --> 28:04.000
I think you're right, Holmes, I said.

28:04.000 --> 28:07.000
I'm certain, said Holmes.

28:07.000 --> 28:10.000
But be careful of what?

28:10.000 --> 28:11.000
Wait.

28:11.000 --> 28:13.000
He's at the window again.

28:13.000 --> 28:18.000
We saw the dark figure of a man who started sending messages again.

28:18.000 --> 28:24.000
This time, he sent the message very quickly, and it was difficult to follow it.

28:24.000 --> 28:26.000
Pay a recolour.

28:26.000 --> 28:28.000
What's that, Watson?

28:28.000 --> 28:31.000
Said Holmes.

28:31.000 --> 28:34.000
Isn't that danger in Italian?

28:34.000 --> 28:35.000
Yes, of course.

28:35.000 --> 28:37.000
It's a danger signal.

28:37.000 --> 28:40.000
Look, there he goes again.

28:40.000 --> 28:42.000
Perry...

28:42.000 --> 28:43.000
What happened?

28:43.000 --> 28:48.000
The light went away, and the third floor of the building was dark.

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
The message suddenly stopped.

28:51.000 --> 28:52.000
What happened?

28:52.000 --> 28:55.000
Holmes and I had the same thought.

28:55.000 --> 28:58.000
Holmes jumped up from his chair.

28:58.000 --> 29:00.000
Watson, this is serious.

29:00.000 --> 29:01.000
He cried.

29:01.000 --> 29:03.000
Something terrible is happening.

29:03.000 --> 29:06.000
Why did the message stop?

29:06.000 --> 29:10.000
I want to call Scotland Yard, but we can't go away now.

29:10.000 --> 29:12.000
What shall we do?

29:12.000 --> 29:13.000
I asked.

29:13.000 --> 29:15.000
We need more facts.

29:15.000 --> 29:16.000
Said Holmes.

29:16.000 --> 29:17.000
Come on, Watson.

29:17.000 --> 29:20.000
Let's go and see what's happening.

29:20.000 --> 29:24.000
Holmes and I walked quickly out to the house and across the street.

29:24.000 --> 29:27.000
I looked back at Mrs. Warren's house.

29:27.000 --> 29:31.000
On the top floor, I could see a woman's head at the window.

29:31.000 --> 29:35.000
She was waiting for the message to continue.

29:35.000 --> 29:40.000
There was a man in a dark coat standing at the door of the red building.

29:40.000 --> 29:43.000
When he saw us, he called...

29:43.000 --> 29:44.000
Holmes!

29:44.000 --> 29:45.000
Gregson.

29:45.000 --> 29:49.000
Said Holmes, looking at the Scotland Yard detective.

29:49.000 --> 29:51.000
Why are you here?

29:51.000 --> 29:54.000
I'm here for the same reason you're here.

29:54.000 --> 29:55.000
Said Gregson.

29:55.000 --> 29:58.000
How did you find out about this?

29:58.000 --> 30:00.000
In a different way from you.

30:00.000 --> 30:01.000
Said Holmes.

30:01.000 --> 30:04.000
I was looking at the signals.

30:04.000 --> 30:05.000
What signals?

30:05.000 --> 30:07.000
Asked Gregson.

30:07.000 --> 30:09.000
The signals from the window?

30:09.000 --> 30:10.000
Said Holmes.

30:10.000 --> 30:14.000
They suddenly stomped and Watson and I came here to see why.

30:14.000 --> 30:17.000
But since the case is in your hands, we can go.

30:17.000 --> 30:19.000
Wait a moment!

30:19.000 --> 30:20.000
Cried Gregson.

30:20.000 --> 30:23.000
I always feel better with you with me.

30:23.000 --> 30:27.000
There is only one way out from these flats, the front door.

30:27.000 --> 30:29.000
So we have him.

30:29.000 --> 30:30.000
Who is he?

30:30.000 --> 30:32.000
Asked Holmes.

30:32.000 --> 30:34.000
You don't know?

30:34.000 --> 30:36.000
Asked Gregson surprised.

30:36.000 --> 30:44.000
Well, for once I know more than you, Mr. Holmes.

30:44.000 --> 30:46.000
Chapter 5.

30:46.000 --> 30:49.000
Giuseppe Gorgiano.

30:49.000 --> 30:54.000
Holmes, Gregson and I were standing outside the tall red building.

30:54.000 --> 31:01.000
Suddenly, a tall man got out of a cab on the other side of the street and came to us.

31:01.000 --> 31:07.000
Mr. Gregson turned to him and said, Mr. Leverton, this is Sherlock Holmes.

31:07.000 --> 31:16.000
Then he turned to Holmes and said, This is Mr. Leverton of Pinkerton's Detective Agency in America.

31:16.000 --> 31:19.000
Sir, I am very pleased to meet you.

31:19.000 --> 31:20.000
Said Holmes.

31:20.000 --> 31:24.000
You're the hero of several important cases.

31:24.000 --> 31:29.000
The young American became embarrassed at the words of Holmes.

31:29.000 --> 31:32.000
I'm on the most important case of my life now.

31:32.000 --> 31:33.000
Said Leverton.

31:33.000 --> 31:36.000
If I can get Gorgiano.

31:36.000 --> 31:38.000
What?

31:38.000 --> 31:40.000
Gorgiano of the Red Circle.

31:40.000 --> 31:42.000
Asked Holmes.

31:42.000 --> 31:45.000
Oh, is he known in Europe too?

31:45.000 --> 31:47.000
Said Leverton.

31:47.000 --> 31:50.000
Well, we know all about him in America.

31:50.000 --> 31:56.000
He's a terrible criminal who killed 50 people and I want to arrest him.

31:57.000 --> 32:02.000
I followed him from New York and I'm watching him carefully here in London.

32:02.000 --> 32:05.000
Mr. Gregson and I followed him to this building.

32:05.000 --> 32:09.000
There is only one door here so he can't get away.

32:09.000 --> 32:15.000
Three men came out of this building after he went in, but he wasn't one of them.

32:15.000 --> 32:18.000
Mr. Holmes talked about signals.

32:18.000 --> 32:20.000
Said Gregson.

32:20.000 --> 32:23.000
I'm sure he knows more than we do.

32:23.000 --> 32:27.000
Holmes explained everything we knew to Gregson and Leverton.

32:27.000 --> 32:30.000
Gorgiano knows we're looking for him.

32:30.000 --> 32:32.000
Said the American detective.

32:32.000 --> 32:33.000
How do you know?

32:33.000 --> 32:34.000
Asked Holmes.

32:34.000 --> 32:37.000
Well, it seems that way, doesn't it?

32:37.000 --> 32:38.000
Said Leverton.

32:38.000 --> 32:43.000
This evening he sent messages to a member of the Red Circle.

32:43.000 --> 32:48.000
There are several members here in London and they know we're looking for them.

32:48.000 --> 32:51.000
What can we do, Mr. Holmes?

32:51.000 --> 32:54.000
We must go up at once and see.

32:54.000 --> 32:55.000
Said Holmes.

32:55.000 --> 32:57.000
But I can't arrest him.

32:57.000 --> 32:58.000
Said Leverton.

32:58.000 --> 33:01.000
I don't have an arrest warrant.

33:01.000 --> 33:04.000
That man is in an empty flat that is not his home.

33:04.000 --> 33:05.000
Said Gregson.

33:05.000 --> 33:07.000
That's a good reason to arrest him.

33:07.000 --> 33:12.000
Then perhaps the New York police can help us to keep him in prison.

33:12.000 --> 33:17.000
We went into the building and Leverton ran up the stairs first to arrest the killer.

33:17.000 --> 33:21.000
But Gregson wanted to be the first and pushed him back.

33:21.000 --> 33:27.000
After all, Gregson was part of the London police and we were in London.

33:27.000 --> 33:32.000
When we got to the third floor, the door of the flat was partly open.

33:32.000 --> 33:36.000
Gregson pushed it open and we all walked in.

33:36.000 --> 33:40.000
Everything was dark and silent inside.

33:40.000 --> 33:45.000
I lit the detective's lantern and suddenly we saw something terrible.

33:45.000 --> 33:48.000
A lot of blood on the floor.

33:48.000 --> 33:53.000
There were red steps on the floor that came from a closed room.

33:53.000 --> 33:58.000
Gregson opened the door and held the lantern in front of him.

33:58.000 --> 34:01.000
We all looked inside the room.

34:01.000 --> 34:09.000
On the floor of the empty room we saw a very big man with a circle of blood around his head.

34:09.000 --> 34:15.000
There was a big knife in his neck and another bigger knife near his hand.

34:15.000 --> 34:17.000
It's Gorgiano.

34:17.000 --> 34:20.000
Cried the American detective loudly.

34:20.000 --> 34:22.000
Gorgiano.

34:22.000 --> 34:25.000
Someone got here before us.

34:25.000 --> 34:28.000
Here is the candle at the window Mr. Holmes.

34:28.000 --> 34:29.000
Said Gregson.

34:29.000 --> 34:31.000
But what are you doing?

34:31.000 --> 34:36.000
Holmes lit the candle and moved it across the windows several times.

34:36.000 --> 34:40.000
Then he blew it out and put it down.

34:40.000 --> 34:42.000
I think this will help.

34:42.000 --> 34:46.000
He said and walked over to the other two men.

34:46.000 --> 34:47.000
Mr. Leviton.

34:47.000 --> 34:50.000
You said three people came out of the building.

34:50.000 --> 34:52.000
Said Holmes.

34:52.000 --> 34:54.000
Did you look at them?

34:54.000 --> 34:56.000
Yes, I did.

34:56.000 --> 34:57.000
Said Leviton.

34:57.000 --> 35:03.000
Was there a man between twenty and thirty years old with dark hair and a beard?

35:03.000 --> 35:04.000
Asked Holmes.

35:04.000 --> 35:06.000
Yes, there was.

35:06.000 --> 35:07.000
Said Leviton.

35:07.000 --> 35:10.000
I think he is your man.

35:10.000 --> 35:11.000
Said Holmes.

35:11.000 --> 35:15.000
That is why I called his lady here.

35:15.000 --> 35:18.000
We all turned around when we heard this.

35:18.000 --> 35:23.000
And at the door there was a tall, beautiful woman.

35:23.000 --> 35:27.000
Mrs. Warren's mysterious lodger.

35:27.000 --> 35:30.000
She slowly walked into the room.

35:30.000 --> 35:36.000
Her face was white and her frightened eyes looked at the body of the huge man on the

35:36.000 --> 35:41.000
floor.

35:41.000 --> 35:44.000
Listening activity.

35:44.000 --> 35:46.000
Hello, Leviton.

35:46.000 --> 35:48.000
How was your trip from America?

35:48.000 --> 35:56.000
Well, I left New York before Christmas and spent Christmas day with my parents in Boston.

35:56.000 --> 36:01.000
Then I celebrated New Year's Eve with my sister and brother, who lived in Salem.

36:01.000 --> 36:08.000
The next day I left Boston Harbor on the new steam ship, American Star.

36:08.000 --> 36:14.000
Last year I sailed from New York to Liverpool on the same ship and it took me twenty-five

36:14.000 --> 36:15.000
long days.

36:15.000 --> 36:18.000
It was a bad trip with terrible weather.

36:18.000 --> 36:20.000
How long did it take you?

36:20.000 --> 36:27.000
Well, it usually takes fifteen days to cross the Atlantic because this new steam ship is

36:27.000 --> 36:28.000
fast.

36:28.000 --> 36:33.500
But this time we stopped in Newfoundland and Ireland to pick up some passengers, so it took

36:33.500 --> 36:36.000
us five extra days.

36:36.000 --> 36:38.000
Do you like travelling by sea?

36:38.000 --> 36:40.000
Oh, I love the sea.

36:40.000 --> 36:45.000
I was born in Boston, and that's right on the Atlantic Ocean.

36:45.000 --> 36:50.000
It's a great city with lots of things to do, but the weather is cold and wet most of

36:50.000 --> 36:54.000
the year, except for a short, hot summer.

36:54.000 --> 36:59.000
I like travelling by train, by horse, and by horse and carriage too.

36:59.000 --> 37:03.000
I took the train across the American continent last year.

37:03.000 --> 37:06.000
I had to arrest a criminal in San Francisco.

37:06.000 --> 37:08.000
I love the sea too.

37:08.000 --> 37:13.000
My family has a house and a little fishing boat in my hometown in Scotland.

37:13.000 --> 37:18.000
If you're free this weekend, we can take the train and go fishing there.

37:18.000 --> 37:19.000
Thanks.

37:19.000 --> 37:21.000
I would love to go.

37:21.000 --> 37:22.000
Good.

37:22.000 --> 37:25.000
I'll pick you up early Saturday morning.

37:25.000 --> 37:30.000
My hotel is near Piccadilly Circus, but we can meet at King's Cross Station.

37:30.000 --> 37:37.000
Well, it's easier if I pick you up at your hotel at half past seven, and then we can go to the station together.

37:37.000 --> 37:39.000
Sounds good, Gregson.

37:40.000 --> 37:47.000
Police and detectives in the 19th century.

37:47.000 --> 37:52.000
In the early part of the 19th century, there was a lot of crime in London.

37:52.000 --> 37:57.000
The city was crowded and criminals could hide easily.

37:57.000 --> 38:02.000
It was often not safe to walk down the dark streets.

38:03.000 --> 38:14.000
In 1829, Sir Robert Bobbie Peel, 1788 to 1850, started the London Metropolitan Police at Scotland Yard.

38:14.000 --> 38:19.000
It was the world's first modern police force with around 1,000 men.

38:19.000 --> 38:27.000
The police wore uniforms and were known as Peelers or Bobbies, both because of Robert Peel's name.

38:28.000 --> 38:32.000
The work of the police was to stop crime in the city streets.

38:32.000 --> 38:36.000
At first, the people of London did not like the police.

38:36.000 --> 38:43.000
But when there was less crime in the city, they started to understand that the police were important.

38:43.000 --> 38:49.000
After 1856, there were police forces all over Great Britain.

38:49.000 --> 38:58.000
The Metropolitan Police Force became a model for the New York City Police in 1850 and for other police forces around the world.

38:58.000 --> 39:04.000
In 1842, the first detective department was started at Scotland Yard.

39:04.000 --> 39:08.000
It had only two inspectors and six sergeants.

39:08.000 --> 39:14.000
Detectives did not wear uniforms and they investigated more complicated crimes.

39:14.000 --> 39:21.000
In 1878, the detective department became the Criminal Investigation Department, CID.

39:21.000 --> 39:26.000
Mr. Gregson in the Red Circle worked for this department.

39:26.000 --> 39:33.000
In the Red Circle, Mr. Leviton worked for the Pinkerton Detective Agency in the United States.

39:33.000 --> 39:42.000
This agency was created by Alan Pinkerton in Chicago in 1850 and today it is the oldest in America.

39:43.000 --> 39:50.000
Alan Pinkerton became famous when he discovered a plan to kill President-elect Abraham Lincoln.

39:50.000 --> 39:59.000
During the American Civil War, President Lincoln used Pinkerton detectives to protect himself and his family.

39:59.000 --> 40:05.000
Sometimes detectives did not do a good job and made a lot of mistakes.

40:05.000 --> 40:13.000
Other times it took them months to solve a case and at times they never solved the case.

40:13.000 --> 40:20.000
Some people paid a private detective like the character of Sherlock Holmes to solve difficult cases.

40:20.000 --> 40:29.000
In Conan Doyle's stories, Sherlock Holmes solved cases with modern scientific methods called forensic methods.

40:29.000 --> 40:38.000
He used chemical analysis, microscopes, fingerprints, photographs, studies of handwriting and footprints.

40:38.000 --> 40:43.000
In real life, detectives did not use these methods yet.

40:43.000 --> 40:49.000
In 1901, Scotland Yard started using fingerprints to solve cases.

40:49.000 --> 40:58.000
Chapter 6 Emilia's Story

40:58.000 --> 41:05.000
The beautiful young woman stood in the empty room and looked sadly at the body of the dead man.

41:05.000 --> 41:09.000
Then she looked at us with her dark eyes.

41:09.000 --> 41:12.000
But you, are you the police?

41:12.000 --> 41:13.000
She asked.

41:13.000 --> 41:15.000
Yes, we are the police.

41:15.000 --> 41:20.000
Said Gregson. She looked around the dark room.

41:20.000 --> 41:22.000
But then, where is Genaro?

41:22.000 --> 41:24.000
She asked.

41:24.000 --> 41:30.000
Genaro Luca is my husband. I am Emilia Luca and we come from New York.

41:30.000 --> 41:35.000
Where is Genaro? He just called me from this window and I ran here.

41:35.000 --> 41:38.000
I called you, said Holmes.

41:38.000 --> 41:41.000
You? How could you call me?

41:41.000 --> 41:43.000
Ask Emilia Luca.

41:43.000 --> 41:46.000
Your secret code was not difficult, madam.

41:46.000 --> 41:48.000
Said Holmes.

41:48.000 --> 41:53.000
We needed you here, so I flashed Vienni at the window.

41:53.000 --> 41:58.000
The beautiful Italian woman looked at Holmes with surprise.

41:58.000 --> 42:01.000
I do not understand how you know these things.

42:01.000 --> 42:03.000
She said.

42:03.000 --> 42:06.000
Giuseppe Gorgiano. How did he?

42:06.000 --> 42:09.000
She stopped and then suddenly said.

42:09.000 --> 42:11.000
Now I understand.

42:11.000 --> 42:15.000
Genaro killed this monster with his strong hands.

42:15.000 --> 42:17.000
Well, Mrs Luca.

42:17.000 --> 42:20.000
Said Gregson, putting his hand on her arm.

42:20.000 --> 42:26.000
I don't really know who you are or what you are, but you know a lot about this case.

42:26.000 --> 42:29.000
Please come to Scotland Yard with me.

42:29.000 --> 42:31.000
One moment, Gregson?

42:31.000 --> 42:32.000
Said Holmes.

42:32.000 --> 42:37.000
I think this lady has several important things to tell us.

42:37.000 --> 42:41.000
Holmes turned to Mrs Luca and said.

42:41.000 --> 42:46.000
Madam, your husband will be arrested for killing this man.

42:46.000 --> 42:51.000
What's Genaro did is very wrong. Do you understand this?

42:51.000 --> 42:55.000
Now that Gorgiano is dead, we are afraid of nothing.

42:55.000 --> 42:56.000
Said Mrs Luca.

42:56.000 --> 42:59.000
He was a terrible monster.

42:59.000 --> 43:04.000
But I know Genaro did the wrong thing. Killing is always wrong.

43:04.000 --> 43:10.000
She was silent for a moment, and her dark eyes were sad.

43:10.000 --> 43:16.000
If I tell you the whole story, perhaps you will understand why my husband killed him.

43:16.000 --> 43:17.000
Very well.

43:17.000 --> 43:19.000
Said Holmes.

43:19.000 --> 43:23.000
Let's close this door and leave everything here.

43:23.000 --> 43:28.000
We can go with this lady to her room and listen to her story.

43:28.000 --> 43:31.000
We all went back to Mrs Warren's house.

43:31.000 --> 43:36.000
Half an hour later, we were sitting in Mrs Luca's small sitting room.

43:36.000 --> 43:40.000
She started telling us her unusual story.

43:40.000 --> 43:45.000
She spoke very quickly, but her English was not good.

43:45.000 --> 43:49.000
I was born in Pazilipo, near the city of Naples, Italy.

43:49.000 --> 43:50.000
She said.

43:50.000 --> 43:55.000
I am the daughter of Augusto Barrelli, a very important man.

43:55.000 --> 43:59.000
Genaro worked for my father, and I loved him.

43:59.000 --> 44:02.000
He was poor, but he was handsome and kind.

44:02.000 --> 44:06.000
My father did not let me marry him, so we ran away together.

44:06.000 --> 44:09.000
We got married in another city.

44:09.000 --> 44:12.000
Then I sold my jewels to get the money to go to America.

44:12.000 --> 44:16.000
We went to New York City four years ago and stayed there.

44:16.000 --> 44:19.000
There were a lot of Italians in New York, and we liked it.

44:19.000 --> 44:22.000
At first, everything went well.

44:22.000 --> 44:28.000
Genaro helped an Italian gentleman called Tito Castellote and became his good friend.

44:28.000 --> 44:35.000
Mr Castellote owns a big company in New York and more than 300 men work for him.

44:35.000 --> 44:40.000
He gave Genaro an important job in his company and was always kind to him.

44:40.000 --> 44:45.000
Mr Castellote was not married, and Genaro was like a son to him.

44:45.000 --> 44:48.000
We both loved him like a father.

44:48.000 --> 44:53.000
Genaro and I rented a small house in Brooklyn, and we were happy together.

44:53.000 --> 44:58.000
Then one evening, Genaro brought an Italian man home with him.

44:58.000 --> 45:03.000
His name was Giuseppe Gorgiano, and he was from Pazilipo too.

45:03.000 --> 45:05.000
He was so big, as you know.

45:05.000 --> 45:08.000
Everything about him was big and frightening.

45:08.000 --> 45:12.000
His voice was loud and he moved his enormous arms about when he talked.

45:12.000 --> 45:15.000
He was too big for our little house.

45:15.000 --> 45:19.000
He never stopped talking with his loud, angry voice.

45:19.000 --> 45:22.000
He came to our house again and again.

45:22.000 --> 45:26.000
Genaro was unhappy when Gorgiano was at our house.

45:26.000 --> 45:29.000
But he sat and listened to Gorgiano talk.

45:29.000 --> 45:33.000
He was a very bad man, and he was always angry.

45:33.000 --> 45:38.000
We were all listening carefully to Mrs Lucas' long story.

45:38.000 --> 45:40.000
I knew something was wrong.

45:40.000 --> 45:44.000
My poor Genaro was terribly afraid of him.

45:44.000 --> 45:50.000
One night, Genaro told me his long story, and I became very sad.

45:50.000 --> 45:55.000
When Genaro was young, he was poor, and the world was against him.

45:55.000 --> 46:00.000
He became a member of a secret society in Naples called the Red Circle.

46:00.000 --> 46:05.000
It was part of the old carbonari, and it did terrible things.

46:05.000 --> 46:10.000
The members of this secret society had to follow the rules and could not leave it.

46:10.000 --> 46:15.000
When we went to America, Genaro was happy because he was far from Naples and the Red Circle.

46:15.000 --> 46:18.000
He wanted to forget about it.

46:18.000 --> 46:23.000
But one evening, he met a member of the Red Circle in New York.

46:23.000 --> 46:25.000
It was Giuseppe Gorgiano.

46:25.000 --> 46:31.000
In the south of Italy, people called him death because he was a terrible killer.

46:31.000 --> 46:39.000
He went to New York because the Italian police wanted to arrest him, and in his new city, he started the Red Circle again.

46:40.000 --> 46:49.000
Chapter 7 The Red Circle

46:49.000 --> 46:54.000
Mrs. Luca continued her story, and we all listened.

46:54.000 --> 47:00.000
One evening, Genaro showed me a letter from Gorgiano with a red circle at the top.

47:00.000 --> 47:05.000
It said there was an important meeting on a certain day, and Genaro had to go.

47:06.000 --> 47:10.000
This was terrible, but then something worse happened.

47:10.000 --> 47:13.000
Gorgiano always came to see us in the evening.

47:13.000 --> 47:16.000
He talked to me a lot, and I did not like it.

47:16.000 --> 47:22.000
He always looked at me with his big ugly eyes. I did not know what to do.

47:22.000 --> 47:26.000
Then one night, Gorgiano came to our house when I was alone.

47:26.000 --> 47:32.000
Genaro was still at work, and Gorgiano told me his secret. He loved me.

47:32.000 --> 47:37.000
He took me in his huge arms and kissed me. It was terrible, and I screamed.

47:37.000 --> 47:44.000
At that moment, Genaro came home and tried to help me. He and Gorgiano fought a lot, and Gorgiano knocked him down and ran away.

47:44.000 --> 47:50.000
He never came back to our house. Gorgiano became our dangerous enemy.

47:50.000 --> 47:58.000
Mrs. Luca stopped for a moment, and looked at us with sad eyes. Then she continued.

47:58.000 --> 48:03.000
A few days later, there was the meeting of the Red Circle, and Genaro had to go.

48:03.000 --> 48:06.000
When he came back, his face was white.

48:06.000 --> 48:12.000
To get money, the secret society blackmailed the rich Italians who lived in New York.

48:12.000 --> 48:18.000
The Red Circle did terrible things to the Italians who did not pay. It even killed them.

48:18.000 --> 48:25.000
The Red Circle sent a letter to a friend, Tito Castellote, and told him to pay.

48:25.000 --> 48:31.000
He was frightened and angry and told the New York police about Gorgiano and the Red Circle.

48:31.000 --> 48:37.000
Gorgiano was very angry and decided to blow up Castellote's house.

48:37.000 --> 48:44.000
The members of the Red Circle chose Genaro to do it. He had to kill his best friend.

48:44.000 --> 48:51.000
My poor Genaro was terrified. He is a good man. He is not a killer. He looked at me and said,

48:51.000 --> 48:56.000
if I don't kill Castellote, Gorgiano will kill us.

48:56.000 --> 49:04.000
It was a terrible night. Genaro and I were very, very afraid. We could not sleep and we did not know what to do.

49:04.000 --> 49:11.000
We talked all night about Gorgiano, the Red Circle, Castellote, and all of the problems we had.

49:11.000 --> 49:18.000
Finally, we decided it was too dangerous to stay in New York, and we had to leave immediately.

49:18.000 --> 49:25.000
But where could we go? I wanted to go back to Pozilipo, but Genaro said that it was not possible.

49:25.000 --> 49:31.000
There were too many of Gorgiano's friends and other Red Circle members there.

49:31.000 --> 49:36.000
So we decided to leave for London because it is a big city and we know no one.

49:36.000 --> 49:40.000
We left early the next morning before the sun came up.

49:40.000 --> 49:47.000
We didn't bring anything with us, only clothes and documents, because we didn't want anyone to realize we were leaving.

49:47.000 --> 49:57.000
We went to the part, but before we sent messages to both Castellote and the police to tell them about Gorgiano's terrible plan.

49:57.000 --> 50:06.000
Well, gentlemen, you will already know the rest of the story. Gorgiano followed us to London, and Genaro found the place for me to hide.

50:06.000 --> 50:12.000
He wanted to go and talk to the Italian police. I never saw my husband during this time.

50:12.000 --> 50:21.000
I don't know where he lived or what he did. The only news from Genaro were the messages in the newspaper.

50:21.000 --> 50:27.000
Then one day from the window I saw two Italians in the street. It was Gorgiano and another man.

50:27.000 --> 50:31.000
They were watching the house. I was alone and frightened.

50:31.000 --> 50:38.000
I read that Genaro's messages in the newspaper. I waited at the window for his signals and saw them.

50:38.000 --> 50:47.000
I knew there was great danger because Gorgiano was near. Fortunately, Genaro was ready for him when he came.

50:47.000 --> 50:54.000
Now, gentlemen, you know the whole story. A long and sad one.

50:54.000 --> 51:02.000
Well, Mr. Gregson said the American detective. Now we know the whole story. What do you think?

51:03.000 --> 51:08.000
Genaro Luca killed a man. Mrs. Luca has to come with me to Scotland Yard.

51:08.000 --> 51:16.000
Said Gregson. The chief of police has to hear her story and talk to her husband. Then he'll decide what to do.

51:16.000 --> 51:18.000
Well, Watson.

51:18.000 --> 51:24.000
Said Holmes. I think our work is done, and it's time to go.

51:24.000 --> 51:28.000
He turned to Emilia and to the other men and said.

51:28.000 --> 51:30.000
Good evening, everyone.

51:30.000 --> 51:40.000
Holmes and I got up, put on our coats and left. It was a cold night as we walked out of Mrs. Warren's house.

